It turns out that all six lines will always pass through the same point, say $P.$  There exist constants $a,$ $b,$ $c,$ and $d$ such that $\overrightarrow{P}$ can always be expressed in the form
\[\overrightarrow{P} = a \overrightarrow{A} + b \overrightarrow{B} + c \overrightarrow{C} + d \overrightarrow{D}.\]Find $a + b + c + d.$

ground_truth.solution:
By constructing a right triangle with legs 1 and $2 \sqrt{2}$ and hypotenuse 3, we see that $\sin \angle BAM$ implies $\tan \angle BAM = \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}}.$

We can draw right triangle $ABC$ so that $AB = 2,$ $AC = 2 \cos A,$ and $BC = 2 \sin A.$  Then $BM = CM = \sin A.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, M;

A = (0,0);
B = (2*sqrt(3),2*sqrt(6));
C = (2*sqrt(3),0);
M = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--M);

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$M$", M, E);
